## Industrial process for ammonia production

This article’s [lead section](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lead_section) feels a bit like a hastily scribbled note – not quite enough to give you the full, unsettling picture. Perhaps it could benefit from a more comprehensive overview of the fundamental aspects.

### The Haber Process: Alchemy of Air, Or Industrial Revolution's Dark Heart?

The [Haber process](/Fritz_Haber), often referred to as the Haber–Bosch process, is the cornerstone of modern industrial [ammonia production](/Ammonia_production). It’s a feat of chemical engineering, transforming the abundant, yet stubbornly inert, [nitrogen](/Nitrogen) from our atmosphere into usable [ammonia](/Ammonia) (NH 3 ) by forcing it to react with [hydrogen](/Hydrogen) (H 2 ). This isn't some gentle dance of molecules; it's a high-stakes negotiation, driven by finely divided [iron](/Iron) acting as a reluctant intermediary, a catalyst that lowers the barrier just enough.

The reaction itself, a deceptive simplicity:

