#### Ammonia Production: The Synthesis Loop

With pure hydrogen secured, it’s mixed with [nitrogen](/Nitrogen) sourced from [air separation](/Air_separation) (though the necessity for further oxygen removal is sometimes debated). The goal is anhydrous [liquid ammonia](/Liquid_ammonia). This is where the Haber–Bosch process truly earns its reputation for being demanding. Achieving a good yield requires high [pressure](/Pressure) and elevated [temperature](/Temperature). Lower temperatures favor the equilibrium towards ammonia, but they also drastically slow down the [reaction kinetics](/Reaction_kinetics), leading to an impractically slow [reaction rate](/Reaction_rate). High pressures, while thermodynamically beneficial, necessitate robust, expensive, and potentially hazardous high-strength pressure vessels that must resist [hydrogen embrittlement](/Hydrogen_embrittlement). The nitrogen molecule, with its tenacious [triple bond](/Triple_bond), is notoriously unreactive.

The core of the process is the ammonia synthesis loop:

