The hydrogen and nitrogen gases are cycled through multiple beds of [catalyst](/Catalyst), with cooling between each stage to manage the [equilibrium constant](/Equilibrium_constant). At each pass, only a fraction of the reactants—around 15%—convert to ammonia. The unreacted gases are then recycled, a continuous loop that eventually pushes the overall conversion rate to an impressive 97%.

The catalysts themselves, typically iron-based promoted with various oxides, are sensitive to impurities. Oxygen-containing compounds, particularly CO, CO 2 , and H 2 O, can poison the catalyst, reducing its effectiveness. While [air separation](/Air_separation) provides relatively pure nitrogen, stringent purification of the hydrogen stream is essential. The large recycle stream, necessary due to the low single-pass conversion, can also lead to the accumulation of inert gases, further impacting efficiency.

The inherent stability of the nitrogen [triple bond](/Triple_bond) means the Haber process relies on catalysts to break it. This presents a delicate balancing act between equilibrium and reaction rate. At room temperature, equilibrium favors ammonia, but the reaction is practically nonexistent. As temperature increases, the rate accelerates, but the equilibrium shifts unfavorably. Following [Le Châtelier's principle](/Le_Ch%C3%A2telier%27s_principle), higher temperatures reduce the equilibrium yield. The reaction's equilibrium constant, K, is highly temperature-dependent:

