Where S* represents an active site on the iron surface. The α-state involves weakening of the N–N bond, a crucial step towards dissociation. The β-state, the surface nitride, is very strongly bound to the surface.

Hydrogen atoms, highly mobile on the surface, then react with these adsorbed nitrogen atoms in a series of steps, forming adsorbed imides (NH ad ), amides (NH 2,ad ), and finally, ammonia (NH 3,ad ), which then desorbs as gaseous ammonia.

The specific crystal faces of iron, particularly the Fe(111) and Fe(211) surfaces, exhibit the highest activity. This is attributed to the presence of C7 sites—iron atoms with seven nearest neighbors—which facilitate the crucial nitrogen dissociation.

